    {
      "id": "intro",
      "type": "theory",
      "title": "At the market: asking the price",
      "body": "# Shopping at the market\n\nAt the **mercado** (market) you need a few words and, above all, one key question: **¿Cuánto cuesta?** — How much does it cost?\n\nKey words:\n\n- *el precio* — the price\n- *el euro* — the euro\n- *la fruta* — the fruit\n- *las manzanas* — the apples\n- *el kilo* — the kilo\n- *barato* — cheap, *caro* — expensive\n\n**Singular or plural?** The verb agrees:\n\n- *¿Cuánto **cuesta**?* — How much does **it** cost? (one thing)\n- *¿Cuánto **cuestan**?* — How much do **they** cost? (several things)\n\nExample: *¿Cuánto **cuesta** el kilo?* (one kilo) versus *¿Cuánto **cuestan** las manzanas?* (the apples, several)."
    },
    {
      "id": "step-cortesia",
      "type": "theory",
      "title": "Ordering politely: quiero / me da / me gustaría",
      "body": "## The politeness ladder\n\nThree ways to order something — from direct to very polite:\n\n1. **quiero** — I want. Direct, the least polite.\n   - *Quiero dos kilos de manzanas.* — I want two kilos of apples.\n2. **me da** — can you give me (literally: you give me). Neutral-polite, very common.\n   - *Me da un kilo de fruta.* — Can you give me a kilo of fruit.\n3. **me gustaría** — I would like. The most polite.\n   - *Me gustaría un kilo de fruta.* — I'd like a kilo of fruit.\n\nAt the market you'll usually hear **me da**. **me gustaría** is especially courteous."
    },
    {
      "id": "step-numeros",
      "type": "theory",
      "title": "Numbers from 100 to 1000",
      "body": "## Big numbers\n\n| Number | Spanish |\n|---|---|\n| 100 | **cien** |\n| 200 | **doscientos** |\n| 300 | **trescientos** |\n| 500 | **quinientos** |\n| 700 | **setecientos** |\n| 900 | **novecientos** |\n| 1000 | **mil** |\n\n**Important:**\n\n- **cien** = exactly 100 (also directly before a noun: *cien euros*). From 101 it becomes **ciento**: *ciento uno* = 101.\n- Three numbers are **irregular** and do NOT follow the pattern:\n  - 500 = **quinientos** (NOT *cincocientos*)\n  - 700 = **setecientos** (NOT *sietecientos*)\n  - 900 = **novecientos** (NOT *nuevecientos*)\n- 1000 = **mil** (no *un* in front)."
    },
